{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486815","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486815"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:45:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:45:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"183"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"183","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/183"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.1,0.14,0.48,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"183"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105087"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"183","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/183"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"183"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87477"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1291"},{"type":"tags","id":"2960"},{"type":"tags","id":"4183"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"31549"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31550"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31551"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38088"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42979"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105087","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105087"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 54-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with two episodes of haematuria and lower bilateral flank pain since this morning. She denies dysuria, difficulty voiding, nausea or vomiting. Five months ago, she was diagnosed with severe bilateral knee osteoarthritis for which she has been managing with regular ibuprofen. She has no other medical history and takes no other medications. She has a 30 pack-year smoking history and drinks 1-2 glasses of red wine a week.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination her temperature is 38.6\u00b0C, pulse 94/min, blood pressure 125/84 mmHg and O2 saturation 99% on room air. She has a slight diffuse maculopapular rash across her back and bilateral flank tenderness on palpation. Bony nodules are noted over many of the distal and proximal interphalangeal joints of the hands. Urinalysis shows blood +++ and protein +.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood tests reveal creatinine 180 \u03bcmol/L (60-110) and estimated glomerular filtration rate 28 mL/min/1.73m\u00b2 (\u0026gt;60).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acute tubular necrosis","Acute pyelonephritis","Systemic lupus erythematosus","Acute tubulointerstitial nephritis","Acute glomerulonephritis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a classic constellation of symptoms suggestive of acute tubulointerstitial nephritis (AIN). The fever, rash, haematuria and renal impairment in the context of NSAID use (ibuprofen) for several months strongly supports this diagnosis. NSAIDs are among the most common medications associated with drug-induced AIN, with symptoms typically developing weeks to months after starting the medication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute tubulointerstitial nephritis\u003C/strong\u003E is an inflammatory condition affecting the renal interstitium and tubules, most commonly caused by drug hypersensitivity reactions. The classic triad of fever, rash, and eosinophilia is present in less than 10% of cases. This patient\u0027s presentation with fever, maculopapular rash, haematuria, proteinuria, and renal impairment after prolonged NSAID use is highly characteristic. NSAIDs cause AIN through both immune-mediated hypersensitivity reactions and direct cytotoxic effects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute tubular necrosis\u003C/strong\u003E (ATN) is characterised by tubular cell injury and death, often due to prolonged ischaemia (for example, in a critically unwell septic patient who has a prolonged period of shock and hence prolonged period of renal hypoperfusion) or nephrotoxics (such as prolonged gentamycin use). These common insults are not referenced in the stem.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute pyelonephritis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with fever, flank pain, and urinary symptoms such as dysuria and frequency. While this patient has fever and flank pain, she specifically denies dysuria. Additionally, pyelonephritis would not explain the rash or the temporal relationship with NSAID use. Urinalysis in pyelonephritis typically shows pyuria and bacteriuria rather than just haematuria and proteinuria.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESystemic lupus erythematosus\u003C/strong\u003E (SLE) can cause lupus nephritis with similar findings, but the absence of SLE manifestations and the clear temporal relationship with NSAID use make this diagnosis less likely. The bony nodules noted on examination are likely consistent with osteoarthritis (Heberden\u0027s and Bouchard\u0027s nodes) than the joint inflammation seen in SLE.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute glomerulonephritis\u003C/strong\u003E, depending on the specific pathology, can present with any of proteinuria, haematuria, renal impairment, hypertension and peripheral oedema. While some features overlap with this patient\u0027s presentation, the presence of fever, rash, and the association with NSAID use point more strongly toward AIN. Glomerulonephritis is characterised by inflammation of the glomeruli rather than the interstitium and tubules.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement of AIN involves discontinuation of the offending drug (ibuprofen in this case), supportive care, and in some cases, corticosteroids to reduce inflammation. Most patients recover renal function after the causative agent is removed, though some may have residual chronic kidney disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acute tubulointerstitial nephritis is characterised by fever, rash, and renal impairment, often triggered by medications like NSAIDs.","NSAIDs are a common cause of acute tubulointerstitial nephritis, with symptoms typically appearing weeks to months after starting the medication."],"references":["Joyce E, Glasner P, Ranganathan S, Swiatecka-Urban A. Tubulointerstitial nephritis: diagnosis, treatment, and monitoring. Pediatric nephrology (Berlin, Germany). 2017;32(4):577-87."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87477"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"183"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87477","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/87477"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-07T09:17:17+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-07T09:17:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"183"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105087"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonym